<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">41106502</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>30</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>20</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1872-8227</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>229</Volume><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Nov</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Diabetes research and clinical practice</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Diabetes Res Clin Pract</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Resistance training enhances metabolic and muscular health and reduces systemic inflammation in middle-aged and older adults with type 2 diabetes: a meta-analysis.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>112941</StartPage><MedlinePgn>112941</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.diabres.2025.112941</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0168-8227(25)00955-6</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>This meta-analysis evaluated the effects of resistance training on insulin resistance, muscle function, and systemic inflammation in middle-aged and older adults (aged 50&#xa0;years and older) with type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM). PubMed, Web of Science, Scopus, and Cochrane CENTRAL were systematically searched from their inception to May 20, 2025. Forty-three randomized controlled trials (n&#xa0;=&#xa0;2012 (55.8&#xa0;% women); mean age 57.8&#xa0;&#xb1;&#xa0;8.4&#xa0;years; mean BMI 30.9&#xa0;&#xb1;&#xa0;3.8&#xa0;kg/m<sup>2</sup>) were included. Resistance training was associated with improvements in markers of insulin resistance, including insulin (mean difference: MD -1.35 &#x3bc;IU/mL), HOMA-IR (MD -1.15), fasting glucose (MD -6.99&#xa0;mg/dL), and HbA1c (MD -0.55&#xa0;%), as well as a modest reduction in BMI (MD -0.37&#xa0;kg/m<sup>2</sup>). Furthermore, resistance training increased muscle mass (MD 0.89&#xa0;kg) and both upper-body (standardized mean difference: SMD 2.28) and lower-body strength (SMD 2.02). A significant reduction in C-reactive protein (CRP; SMD -0.80) was observed, though no significant changes were found for tumor necrosis factor-&#x3b1; (TNF-&#x3b1;) or interleukin-6 (IL-6). Overall, resistance training provides consistent benefits for insulin sensitivity, muscle function, and systemic inflammation in middle-aged and older adults with T2DM, supporting its role as an important adjunct to lifestyle-based diabetes management strategies aimed at promoting healthier aging.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Jingwen</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Physical Education, Henan Normal University, Xinxiang, Henan, 475100, China. Electronic address: 1575047179@qq.com.cn.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Fan</LastName><ForeName>Shiqian</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Physical Education, Henan University, Kaifeng, Henan, 475100, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Jianshe</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Physical Education, Henan Normal University, Xinxiang, Henan, 475100, China. Electronic address: 522851148@qq.com.cn.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D017418">Meta-Analysis</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D000078182">Systematic Review</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>15</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>Ireland</Country><Medline